type="user">jms-0011</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-0011.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Chapter 3: the theory of universes">Chapter 3: the theory of universes</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>19</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Universes started their life in the <fr:link
type="local"
href="sga-4.xml"
addr="sga-4"
title="Théorie des topos et cohomologie étale des schémas (SGA 4)">Grothendieck school of algebraic geometry</fr:link> as a technical device to circumvent the annoyance that there cannot be a “set of all sets”; a universe is a set of enough sets, and whilst a universe cannot contain itself, it may nonetheless lie within an even bigger universe. Several important developments in the theory of universes from the 1970s onward by <fr:link
type="local"
href="jeanb%C3%A9nabou.xml"
addr="jeanbénabou"
title="Jean Bénabou">Bénabou</fr:link>, <fr:link
type="local"
href="permartinl%C3%B6f.xml"
addr="permartinlöf"
title="Per Martin-Löf">Martin-Löf</fr:link>, Dybjer, <fr:link
type="local"
href="martinhofmann.xml"
addr="martinhofmann"
title="Martin Hofmann">Hofmann</fr:link>, <fr:link
type="local"
href="thomasstreicher.xml"
addr="thomasstreicher"
title="Thomas Streicher">Streicher</fr:link>, <fr:link
type="local"
href="steveawodey.xml"
addr="steveawodey"
title="Steve Awodey">Awodey</fr:link>, and others have collided to deliver the present-day understanding of the centrality of universes in semantics: a model of type theory is just a special kind of universe in a special kind of category. This chapter provides expository background on the theory of universes, including a novel account of open and closed subuniverses to reflect the recollement theory of topoi from <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-0010.xml"
addr="jms-0010"
title="Chapter 2: the language of topoi">Chapter 2</fr:link>. These open and closed subuniverses will play a critical role in the development of synthetic Tait computability in subsequent chapters.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
